05505nam a2200805Ia 9780231558174DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2023018173  a97802315581747 a10.7312/krep209902doi  a(DE-B1597)673033  a(OCoLC)1414454927  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHB801b.K728 2023 4aHB801b.K728 2024 7aBUS0690302bisacsh04a338.5/212223/eng/202306281 aKreps, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArguing About Tastes :bModeling How Context and Experience Change Economic Preferences /cDavid Kreps. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKenneth J. Arrow Lecture Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Gary Becker on Prenups -- t1. De Gustibus Non Est Disputandum -- t2. Intrinsic Motivation -- t3. Internalizing the Welfare of Specific Others -- t4. Two (Or Three) Heterodox Books -- t5. Choice, Preference, and Utility in Dynamic Contexts -- t6. Some (Social) Psychology -- t7. Intrinsic Motivation Undermined by Extrinsic Rewards? -- t8. Why Are “Social Promises” Unsecured? -- t9. The Quality of Kreps’s Performance Matters as Well -- t10. Intrinsic Motivation to Do What, Exactly? -- t11. Internalization of the Other Party’s Welfare -- t12. Dynamics Based on Bem’s Self-Perception Theory -- t13. Should Economists Move in These Directions? -- tCommentary -- tCommentary -- tResponse to the Comments of Professors Stiglitz and Casella -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMainstream economics considers individual preferences to be fixed and unchanging. Although psychologists and other social scientists explore how tastes are formed, influenced, and evolve, it is not considered “proper” in orthodox economics to do so. Arguing About Tastes makes the case that economists should abandon the principle that preferences are fixed and instead incorporate into their work how context and experience shape individual tastes.David M. Kreps argues that the discipline must account for dynamic personal tastes when it comes to understanding social exchange, emphasizing human resource management and on-the-job behavior. He develops formal models that illustrate the power of intrinsic motivation and show why applying extrinsic incentives can be counterproductive. Kreps weighs the advantages and disadvantages of the principle de gustibus non est disputandum: there is no arguing about tastes. He calls for a new era of economics in which preferences are taken into account—and not for granted.Arguing About Tastes concludes with responses by the distinguished economists Alessandra Casella and Joseph E. Stiglitz and a final reply by Kreps.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aConsumers' preferences2DLC. 0aConsumers' preferences. 0aDemand (Economic theory) 0aDemand (Economic theory)2DLC. 0aDemand (Economic theory). 0aGame theory2DLC. 0aGame theory. 0aMicroeconomics2DLC. 0aMicroeconomics. 0aUncertainty2DLC. 0aUncertainty. 0aUtility theory2DLC. 0aUtility theory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh1 aCasella, Alessandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStiglitz, Joseph E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2023 Englishz978311131907008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 E